knowledge_graph.title: Leek
knowledge_graph.description: A leek is a vegetable, a cultivar of Allium ampeloprasum, the broadleaf wild leek. The edible part of the plant is a bundle of leaf sheaths that is sometimes erroneously called a stem or stalk. The genus Allium also contains the onion, garlic, shallot, scallion, chives, and Chinese onion.

related_questions.question: Does leek taste like onion?
related_questions.snippet: What Do Leeks Taste Like? Leeks taste like a mild version of an onion, with the same base flavor but far less intensity. They are delicate and sweeter than other members of its cultivar group. Traditionally, the white part and light green middle are eaten, while the green tops are often discarded.

related_questions.snippet: Mostly just the white and light green parts are eaten, though the darker green parts have plenty of flavor and can either be cooked longer to tenderize them, or used when making homemade soup stock.

related_questions.question: What are leeks called in America?
related_questions.snippet: What Are Leeks Called in America? Leeks are called leeks in the States but there are also wild leeks (aka ramps) and a type of allium in Spain called a calçot, which are larger than spring onions but smaller than leeks.

buttons.subtitle: What Do Leeks Taste Like?
buttons.title: What Are Leeks and How Do You Cook With Them? - Allrecipes
buttons.snippet: Leeks have a mildly sweet flavor that is reminiscent of other alliums, such as onions, shallots, garlic, and chives. They are often used the way onions are — as part of a base of flavors for soups, stews, and other long-cooking dishes. However, their more mild flavor means they can be enjoyed on their own as well.
snippet_highlighted_words: mildly sweet flavor that is reminiscent of other alliums, such as onions, shallots, garlic, and chives

buttons.subtitle: Is Leek Good For You
buttons.title: Health Benefits of Leeks - WebMD
buttons.snippet: Leeks are rich in flavonoids, especially one called kaempferol. Flavonoids are antioxidants and may have anti-inflammatory, anti-diabetic, and anticancer properties, as well as other health benefits. Definite proof of these health benefits of leeks will depend upon future studies with humans.

buttons.snippet: Leeks are alliums, so they're related to garlic, chives, shallots, and onions. Tasting them, you can tell. They have a sweet, oniony flavor that adds depth to soups, stews, pastas, and more!

buttons.subtitle: How Do You Eat Leeks
buttons.title: What Are Leeks? How to Clean, Cut, and Cook Them - Forks Over Knives
buttons.snippet: When leeks are sliced or chopped, they can be used in place of onions or shallots in soups, stews, and casseroles. You can also showcase their subtle, sweet flavor in pasta dishes like our Red Lentil Rotini with Silken Leeks and Shiitakes or Vegan Penne with Artichokes, Leeks, and Lentils.

buttons.subtitle: What Are Leeks For?
buttons.title: What Are Leeks and Wild Ramps? 10 Impressive Benefits - Healthline
buttons.snippet: Leeks are a rich source of antioxidants, particularly polyphenols and sulfur compounds. Antioxidants fight oxidation, which damages your cells and contributes to illnesses like diabetes, cancer, and heart disease.

buttons.subtitle: What Part Of The Leek Is Good
buttons.title: Leeks: Don't Throw Away the Green Part! - La Cucina Italiana
buttons.snippet: With leeks, the general trend is to use the white part and throw away the green. This green part contains a lot of vitamin C and it can be used in many recipes. You only have to remove a few centimeters of the usually woody upper part from the leaves. Boiled leaves can be used for sauces, soups or casseroles.

buttons.subtitle: What Is Edible On A Leek
buttons.title: All About: Leeks (How to Cut and Clean) - Fork in the Kitchen
buttons.snippet: The most edible parts of leeks are the bottom white and light green parts because they are tender and have the most flavor. The dark green parts are technically edible but to a lesser extent because they are quite tough. If you do want to eat the dark green parts, be sure to saute them well so they soften.
snippet_highlighted_words: bottom white and light green parts

buttons.title: What Are Leeks? | Cooking School - Food Network
buttons.snippet: What Part of the Leek Do You Eat? Typically, their white root ends are sliced up and pureed into soup or roasted or sautéed, while their tougher dark green ends can be added whole to soups or stocks for extra aromatic flavor.
